tire-bunkers and business men of tho\ncity, saying thoy had done moro In\nthe financial troubles than congress\ncould have done. Thero waa alto\ngether too much general crltjclsm of\nbusiness mon, he said, and corpora\ntions wore hare to day, tho country\nunder tho present conditions not bo\nIng oblo t0 get on without them.\nSecretnry Cortolyou, who was ox\npected, was unablo to attend and sent\nn letter of regret which polntod out\nthat his duties In Washington requir\ned his presence attontlon. When Sen\nator Spooncr was Introduced tho or\nchestra playod \"We Won't Go Homo\nUntil Morning.\"\nSTATE AND VICINITY\nToogarden An unsuccessful attempt\nwas mado to wreck the south-bound\nErlo- passongor train between Toczar-\nden nnd Coleman, sovoral mllos north\nof Lisbon.\nI.Uhou John O'Donnol, aged about\n45, wai badly, and It Is 'oared fatal\nly Injured, In tho Big Voln Coal Cos\nmlnos nt Sallnovlllo.\nSalom Andrew Lahondony, a Oor\nman, wns Instrumental Wodnesday eve\nning In having his mother, nn ngo.1\nGerman lady, locked up on a charge ot\nIntoxication.\nMnsslllon But for tho refusal of\ntwo or thrco saloonkcopera to closo\ntholr places of business, It Is said,\nMaselllon would bo a clo&od town on\nSundays.\nMorlotta Edgar Grubb, his wlfo and\nbaby woro burned to death In their\nfarm homo.\nLisbon Drillers operating for tho\nDevonian Oil Co. ot Pittsburg drilled\nIn a gas well yestorduy on tho Sam\nuol Williams farm, two mlloa south\nwest ut town. Tbo well shows a fair\npressure\nYoungstown Tlio llfo ot Mro. Mary\nSutala, who sustained torrlble burns\nWednesday morning whllo protecting\nhor two llttlo girls from tho flames if\nan oxplodlng oil lamp at their homo\non VJno street, went out at 3 o'clock\nThursday morning at tho City hospi\ntal, where eho had lain slnco tho ac-cldont.\nQooto on Michaelmas Day,\nTho origin ot cntlng gooso on\nMichaelmas Day dates from tbo tlmo\nof Queen Ellzaboth. On her way to\nTilbury Fort on Sept. 20, 1CS9, sho\ndined on roast gooso and Burgundy\nwlno. With tho last glass sho drank\n\"Destruction to tho Spanish Armada.\"\nAs she drained tho glass news carao\nof tho destruction ot tho Spanish\nfleet by a \"storm. Thereupon sho orr\ndercd that roast gooso should bo\nserved for her every year on that\nday, and the custom soon becamo\ngeneral among tho people.\nNotice to Contractors.\nSealed proposals will bo received by\ntho Commissioners of Stark County up\nuntil noon Dccombor 10th, 1907, for\nbuilding nn addition to Uio Bollor\nHouso at tho Stark County Infirmary,\nthe drawings nnd specifications for\nsnmo nro now oa.fllo at tho ofllco ot\ntho Auditor, Said proposal is to bo\nmado out on blank forrtu which will\nbo furnlshod and each bid must be ac\ncompanied by ft certified chock for\n$200.00 mado payable to tho Commis\nsioners ot Stark Co. which is to bo for\nfeited to them In the event that tho\nbidder rofusod to enter Into contract\nwith good and oufflolent bond when\nnotified that this work has boon award\ned to him.\nCommissioners rosorvo tho right to\nreject any or all bids.\nM. W. OBDRLIN, Auditor.\nFIFTH AND MARKET S T R E E X S5\nCALDWELL'S\nSPECIALS FOR TODAY\n$1.25 Kid Gloves 69c\nTbeso splendid 2-clasp Kid Clloves will bo sold today at 69c a pair; sizes 0 to 7i,\nBLACK8, REDS, BROWN8, TAN GREY.\nWe will no, sell over two pair to a customer and this salo Is limited to ono day.\n$1.50 Wool Union Suits 79c\nTODAY ONLY 100 Wool Uulon Suits for Iadlos will be Bold nt tho remorkablo\nprice of 7iifl suit alsos 4, C and 0. This underwear Is tho well known .OwltSi\nt brandy that sells In nil stores at Jl.W. On salo today, (only blacks).\n$1.00 Shirt Waists. $1.00\nHeavy cotton plaid and white or black\nBrllllantlne waists, 4 AA\nFriday XUU\nCOc. Boys' Shirts 26c.\nHeavy fleeced undershirts for boys,,\nsizes 21 to 82, regular 90\nCOc grado, today CkOK\n76c Women's Wool Yests 49c\nExtra nice 75 o Wool Vosts (no punts)\nwill be sold today 1QA\n$1.60 Men's Umbrellas $1.00\n2S Inch Umbrellas, ta